BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE:NC State University
CATEGORIES:Information Session,Tours and Open Houses
DESCRIPTION:March is Women's History Month\, and the JC Raulston Arboretum 
 (JCRA) will celebrate with a special Plant-Lover's Tour: Ladies' Choice. Jo
 in JCRA Nursery Technician Sophia McCusker and master's student and former 
 JCRA intern Eileen Gahan as they lead you through the garden\, highlighting
  the plants they love most. From early spring showstoppers already bursting
  into bloom to dependable favorites that deserve a little more appreciation
 \, this tour is all about personal picks with professional insight.\n\nAnd 
 because it's Ladies' Choice\, you can expect a few wild cards on the tour\,
  such as plants that do great in containers and are impossible to kill in t
 he nursery and plants that definitely do not grow in Ireland but seem to do
  amazing here. \n\nCome see what makes the cut when McCusker and Gahan get 
 to choose their favorites and discover a few new must-have plants for your 
 own garden.
DTEND:20260303T190000Z
DTSTAMP:20260326T025710Z
DTSTART:20260303T180000Z
GEO:35.794251;-78.699671
LOCATION:JC Raulston Arboretum
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:Plant-Lover's Tour: Ladies' Choice
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_52010590613807
URL:https://calendar.ncsu.edu/event/plant-lovers-tour-ladies-choice
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE:NC State University
CATEGORIES:Workshops and Training
DESCRIPTION:Artificial intelligence (AI) tools\, such as ChatGPT\, have bec
 ome a part of our lives\, supporting us academically\, professionally and e
 motionally — but how can we use them in healthy ways? This interactive work
 shop will explore AI’s impact on mental health\, including dependency\, soc
 ial effects\, anxiety and depression concerns and academic pressure. We’ll 
 discuss the risks of using AI as a therapist\, how AI’s cheerleading tone c
 an mislead users and how prompt engineering plus human support can help you
  set healthier boundaries.
DTEND:20260303T213000Z
DTSTAMP:20260326T025710Z
DTSTART:20260303T200000Z
GEO:35.787562;-78.669711
LOCATION:D.H. Hill Jr. Library\, Cyma Rubin Visualization Gallery
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:Healthy Boundaries for AI Use: A Digital Wellness Discussion
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_52249102575591
URL:https://calendar.ncsu.edu/event/healthy-boundaries-for-ai-use-a-digital
 -wellness-discussion
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE:NC State University
CATEGORIES:Community Events
DESCRIPTION:THE HONEST STUDIO: DESIGN TALKS\n\nA candid\, creative conversa
 tion about how real design careers take shape. No slides. No script. Just f
 ive designers sharing defining moments: the early stumbles\, the unexpected
  breakthroughs\, and the pivots that changed everything. We’ll explore crea
 tive growth\, finding direction\, and navigating  an ever-evolving industry
 . Come curious\, join the dialogue\, and\ndiscover what’s possible on your 
 own design path.\n\nPanelists:\n\nMARIA RADDATZ Creative Director\, Bolton 
 & Menk\n\nMaria leads the in-house design team with clear direction\, helpi
 ng shape ideas and improve results. She brings steady leadership and a stro
 ng creative vision to every project\, from complex work to daily design rev
 iews and team support. In her talk\, she’ll share how she works with differ
 ent personalities\, guides cross-team efforts\, and handles changing workpl
 ace technology.\n\nHer Key Question: How did you navigate the transition fr
 om being a hands-on creative to managing creatives— and what surprised you 
 most?\n\nMACK GARRISON Co-Founder\, Dash Studio\n\nMack is a community-mind
 ed creative known for strong work and a client list that includes J.P. Morg
 an\, Coinbase\, Red Hat\, IBM\, Lenovo\, and more. He is the Co-Founder and
  Director of Content at Dash Studio\, a high-end animation and video agency
  that turns complex ideas into clear\, meaningful stories. His talk will co
 ver creative entrepreneurship\, communication\, and work–life balance.\n\nH
 is Key Question: What mindset shift helped you see pitching as part of your
  design practice—communicating problem-solving and impact instead of market
 ing yourself?\n\nAMBER HARMON Design Manager\, Visit Raleigh\n\nAmber spent
  adecade in a startup fashion/lifestyle brand. Growing from designer to cre
 ative director\, she brought art to life from sketch to runway in ways you 
 can wear and experience. Her work expanded from print/digital to fashion de
 sign and events. Now at the Greater Raleigh CVB (Visit Raleigh)\, her passi
 on for visual storytelling shapes and refines the visual identity of Wake C
 ounty. She will focus on workplace navigation\, vendor relationships\, and 
 work-life balance. \n\nHer Key Question: How did fashion influence the way 
 you tell visual stories and build brands?\n\nJARRETT FULLER College of Desi
 gn\, NC State\n\nWhile Jarrett is an assistant professor and the director o
 f undergraduate programs in graphic design at North Carolina State Universi
 ty\, he also hosts the design podcast Scratching the Surface\, and runs his
  independent studio\, twenty-six. He focuses on books\, brands\, and websit
 es alongside research into design discourse and alternative practices. As a
  panelist\, he will discuss design identity\, creative problem-solving\, an
 d career growth.\n\nHis Key Question: What combination of craft (tools)\, s
 ystems thinking\, and business acumen has proved most decisive in your care
 er so far—and why that mix?\n\nIAN WENSTRAND Illustration Freelance\n\nIan 
 Wenstrand is a Raleigh-based artist and illustrator known for detailed\, co
 lorful digital work that mixes cityscapes\, sci-fi\, technology\, and playf
 ul characters. His clients include Citrix\, Pendo\, the City of Raleigh\, F
 ilmNC\, Band Together\, and UX Y’all\, and his work has been featured in Ko
 taku. In 2017\, he wrote and illustrated the children’s bookPlugged In. His
  session will focus on freelance expectations\, self-advocacy\, and work re
 sponsibility. \n\nHis Key Question: How do you manage situations where a cl
 ient or project goes over budget or requests work for free?
DTEND:20260303T230000Z
DTSTAMP:20260326T025710Z
DTSTART:20260303T214500Z
GEO:35.784712;-78.665536
LOCATION:Kamphoefner Hall\, Burns Auditorium
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:The Honest Studio: Design Talks
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_52010824690344
URL:https://calendar.ncsu.edu/event/the-honest-studio-design-talks
END:VEVENT
