BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE:NC State University
CATEGORIES:Lectures and Talks
DESCRIPTION:Join us for the spring 2026 graphic design lecture series. \n\n
 Ashleigh Axios: Designing where it matters: alternative paths in civic desi
 gn\n\nWhat does it look like to build a design career focused on public imp
 act? In this talk\, Ashleigh Axios shares her creative journey through gove
 rnment\, consulting\, and civic innovation\, alongside case studies spannin
 g national digital services and crisis response. She’ll offer a candid look
  at the current moment in civic design and explore where ethical\, systems-
 minded designers can make the greatest impact. Leave with a clearer sense o
 f alternative career paths and the role design can play in shaping public s
 ystems.\n\nAshleigh Axios is the CEO of Public Servants\, a public interest
  firm\, and a former Obama White House Creative Director. She’s also a RISD
  trustee\, past AIGA Board Chair\, and founder of DotGov Design. Her work b
 ridges design\, equity\, and public systems to create sustainable\, people-
 centered impact.
DTEND:20260305T223000Z
DTSTAMP:20260326T025710Z
DTSTART:20260305T213000Z
GEO:35.784712;-78.665536
LOCATION:Kamphoefner Hall\, Burns Auditorium
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:Graphic & Experience Design Lecture: Ashleigh Axios
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_51889030578138
URL:https://calendar.ncsu.edu/event/graphic-design-lecture-ashleigh-axios
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE:NC State University
CATEGORIES:Lectures and Talks
DESCRIPTION:Join the Department of Religious Studies for the annual Impact 
 of Religion Lecture. Rebecca Peters\, professor of religious studies at Elo
 n University and president of the Society of Christian Ethics\, will be our
  speaker. Her talk is titled "Abortion & Religion: Exploring the Epistemolo
 gical Insights of Christian Women Having Abortions." Peters will trace the 
 religious roots of the highly politicized abortion debate in the U.S. She w
 ill also discuss insights from the Abortion & Religion project\, a major re
 search study that includes interviews with Jewish\, Christian\, and Muslim 
 people who have had abortions in the United States.
DTEND:20260305T230000Z
DTSTAMP:20260326T025710Z
DTSTART:20260305T213000Z
GEO:35.785509;-78.668001
LOCATION:111 Lampe Drive Building\, 218
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:Impact of Religion Lecture: Abortion & Religion
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_51904945144528
URL:https://calendar.ncsu.edu/event/abortion-religion-exploring-insights-fr
 om-christian-women-having-abortions
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE:NC State University
CATEGORIES:Community Events,Exhibitions
DESCRIPTION:Come to the Gregg Museum of Art & Design for an evening gallery
  walkthrough with the curatorial and collections teams. We will explore the
  exhibition Through Our Eyes\, In Our Hands: Prioritizing Indigenous Knowle
 dge in Museums. This exhibit foregrounds Native perspectives on the steward
 ship of cultural belonging and the histories and futures of repatriation. T
 hrough Indigenous voices and frameworks\, the exhibition reframes long-held
  museum practices\, asking visitors to consider questions of authority\, ow
 nership\, knowledge and care.\n\nLee Chavis-Tartaglia\, the Native American
  Graves Protection and Repatriation Act (NAGPRA) collections assistant\, an
 d Meredith Osborne\, a curatorial assistant\, will offer insight into the s
 ignificance of the NAGPRA. They will also share archival materials\, person
 al accounts\, community-based narratives in the exhibition and the process 
 of developing the exhibition from start to finish.
DTEND:20260305T230000Z
DTSTAMP:20260326T025711Z
DTSTART:20260305T220000Z
GEO:35.784762;-78.661636
LOCATION:Gregg Museum of Art & Design\, Front Lobby
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:Prioritizing Indigenous Knowledge in Museums
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_51949067080542
URL:https://calendar.ncsu.edu/event/a-closer-look-museum-staff-unpack-throu
 gh-our-eyes-in-our-hands-prioritizing-indigenous-knowledge-in-museums
END:VEVENT
