BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE:NC State University
CATEGORIES:Lectures and Talks,Community Events
DESCRIPTION:Please join NC State's Climate and Sustainability Academy (CaSA
 ) for the second event in our three-part CaSA Conversations series. Join us
  for coffee\, breakfast and networking from 8:45 to 9 a.m.\, followed by a 
 panel discussion on campus nature and health.\n\nDawn Rodriguez-Ward\, an a
 cademic program manager at the Climate and Sustainability Academy and an En
 vironmental First Year Program instructor\, will moderate the panel discuss
 ion. The panelists are:\n\nMegan Lupek\, an associate teaching professor an
 d the co-director of the Environmental Sciences ProgramTommy Holden\, teach
 ing professor and coordinator of the Outdoor Leadership minorDr. Courtney H
 inton\, campus medical directorThis event is free to attend\, but registrat
 ion is required.
DTEND:20260310T140000Z
DTSTAMP:20260326T025711Z
DTSTART:20260310T124500Z
GEO:35.771067;-78.676515
LOCATION:Partners I – NC State University
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:CaSA Conversations: Campus Nature and Health
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_52129359803941
URL:https://calendar.ncsu.edu/event/casa-conversations-campus-nature-and-he
 alth
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE:NC State University
CATEGORIES:Community Events,Student Life,Tours and Open Houses
DESCRIPTION:Please join us on a monthly basis for a walk through the Lake R
 aleigh Woods\, one of NC State's hidden gems and Hallowed Spaces. The hike 
 is about 1.5 miles. Below are a few things to remember for the hike:\n\nMak
 e sure to park in the northwest corner of the Park Alumni Center parking lo
 t a little before 9 a.m. for a brief safety conversation. Parking is free f
 or everyone. Wear closed-toed shoes and bring a water bottle.Check the weat
 her forecast and wear weather-appropriate clothing on the hike.Restrooms ar
 e available in the Alumni Center. There are no facilities on the trail.The 
 hike will last approximately 90 minutes but could be a little shorter depen
 ding on the group's pace. Space is limited for each hike. Be sure to regist
 er.\n\nLake Raleigh Woods Hikes are recognized as a Campus Nature Rx Progra
 m\, an international movement built around encouraging universities and the
 ir communities to engage with the physical and mental health benefits of be
 ing in nature.
DTEND:20260310T143000Z
DTSTAMP:20260326T025711Z
DTSTART:20260310T130000Z
GEO:35.767879;-78.677586
LOCATION:Lake Raleigh
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:Lake Raleigh Woods Hike
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_51435730830268
URL:https://calendar.ncsu.edu/event/lake-raleigh-woods-hike
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE:NC State University
CATEGORIES:Exhibitions
DESCRIPTION:The House of Ideas: Plants in Art will be on exhibit in the Cab
 aniss Gallery in the Historic Chancellor’s Residence every Tuesday-Saturday
  until May 31\, 2026. This exhibition is a participatory learning lab that 
 uncovers the artistic representation of plants in our lives and in the natu
 ral world. It features objects from the Gregg Museum of Art & Design Collec
 tion that depict the roles of plants from nourishment and communal living t
 o the scientific study of human health. The House of Ideas offers a relaxin
 g room for botanical sketching and a self-guided tour of the museum’s garde
 n.
DTEND:20260310T210000Z
DTSTAMP:20260326T025711Z
DTSTART:20260310T140000Z
GEO:35.784762;-78.661636
LOCATION:Gregg Museum of Art & Design\, Cabaniss Gallery
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:The House of Ideas: Plants in Art Exhibition
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_50392730686724
URL:https://calendar.ncsu.edu/event/the-house-of-ideas-plants-in-art
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE:NC State University
CATEGORIES:Exhibitions
DESCRIPTION:Through Our Eyes\, In Our Hands: Prioritizing Indigenous Knowle
 dge in Museums will be on display at the Gregg Museum of Art & Design Tuesd
 ay-Saturday until June 27\, 2026. This exhibition foregrounds Native perspe
 ctives on the stewardship of cultural belongings and the history and future
  of repatriation. This exhibition transforms the museum into a site of lear
 ning\, self-examination\, and responsibility.\n\nVisitors are guided throug
 h the intertwined histories of museum collecting\, cultural consultation\, 
 and the journey to repatriation. Archival materials\, personal accounts\, a
 nd community-based narratives offer insight into the significance of the Na
 tive American Graves Protection and Repatriation Act (NAGPRA) and the ongoi
 ng work beyond its legal requirements. Rather than presenting repatriation 
 as a transactional process\, this exhibition emphasizes its cultural\, spir
 itual\, emotional\, and relational dimensions—its power to restore connecti
 ons and honor ancestors and communities.
DTEND:20260310T210000Z
DTSTAMP:20260326T025711Z
DTSTART:20260310T140000Z
GEO:35.784762;-78.661636
LOCATION:Gregg Museum of Art & Design
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:Through Our Eyes\, In Our Hands: Prioritizing Indigenous Knowledge 
 in Museums
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_52426846541997
URL:https://calendar.ncsu.edu/event/through-our-eyes-in-our-hands-prioritiz
 ing-indigenous-knowledge-in-museums
END:VEVENT
