BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE:NC State University
CATEGORIES:Community Events
DESCRIPTION:NC State’s annual Take Back the Night is an event that reclaims
  the night and our campus for survivors of sexual assault. Join us at Staff
 ord Commons for a resource fair at 4:30 p.m. and the main program at 5 p.m.
  A rally and a march across campus will follow. The evening will culminate 
 in a powerful Survivor Speak Out at Talley in the Currituck-Hatteras Ballro
 om immediately following the march. Counselors will be available for privat
 e counseling in the Ocracoke Ballroom in Talley during the speak out. The e
 vening will conclude with a gathering at the Women’s Center in Talley that 
 will include food\, healing and community buildig.\n\nTake Back the Night i
 s part of the university's Sexual Assault Awareness Month observance in Apr
 il. Please visit the Women's Center website to learn about more events happ
 ening during Sexual Assault Awareness Month.
DTEND:20260409T010000Z
DTSTAMP:20260326T025712Z
DTSTART:20260408T200000Z
GEO:35.783848;-78.670939
LOCATION:Stafford Commons
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:Take Back the Night
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_52329846938469
URL:https://calendar.ncsu.edu/event/take-back-the-night-4262
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE:NC State University
CATEGORIES:Lectures and Talks
DESCRIPTION:Greg Lindquist’s work examines the intersection of landscape\, 
 industry\, and environmental change through painting\, video\, and research
 -based practice. Drawing on long-term projects including the Newtown Creek 
 series in Brooklyn and more recent wildfire paintings\, his work considers 
 how contemporary landscapes are shaped by infrastructure\, the forces of ge
 ntrification\, extraction\, and atmospheric conditions. A reception will fo
 llow in the Design Library in Brooks Hall\, where Lindquist’s Study for New
 town Creek Series will be newly installed and on view as part of the NC Sta
 te College of Design collection. Greg Lindquist\, Heatwave (105 Wildfires B
 urn Across 35 Towns in Turkey)\, 2024\nOil\, metallic\, and iridescent pigm
 ent on linen on panel\nWorking between studio practice and field research\,
  Lindquist documents sites where ecological systems and industrial processe
 s overlap—locations where air\, water\, and built structures form complex e
 nvironmental relationships. These investigations often involve collaboratio
 n with scientists\, environmental organizations\, and local communities\, p
 roducing works that move between observation\, documentation\, mapping\, an
 d reimagined abstraction.\nThe lecture will trace the development of these 
 projects over the past two decades\, from early paintings of Brooklyn’s gen
 trification\, essay-film experiments\, to recent work addressing climate-dr
 iven wildfires. The talk coincides with the installation of Lindquist’s pai
 nting Study for Newtown Creek Series in the NC State College of Design Libr
 ary. About the Artist  Greg Lindquist is a Brooklyn-based artist whose work
  examines landscape\, ecology\, and environmental change. Lindquist has exh
 ibited widely\, including at DC Moore Gallery\, the Cameron Art Museum\, th
 e Brooklyn Academy of Music\, the University of Arizona Museum of Art\, and
  the North Carolina Museum of Art. He studied at the Whitney Museum of Amer
 ican Art Independent Study Program and holds degrees from NC State Universi
 ty and Pratt Institute
DTEND:20260408T223000Z
DTSTAMP:20260326T025712Z
DTSTART:20260408T213000Z
GEO:35.784712;-78.665536
LOCATION:Kamphoefner Hall\, Burns Auditorium
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:MADTech Lecture: Greg Lindquist
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_52267653859799
URL:https://calendar.ncsu.edu/event/madtech-lecture-greg-lindquist
END:VEVENT
